    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that dancer analogy makes sense, but it still feels a bit weird. i keep reading about how einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did he call it spooky? it sounds like there's something more to it than just particles being linked.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein's \"spooky action at a distance\" comment was a reflection of his discomfort with the idea that information could be transmitted instantaneously between entangled particles, seemingly violating the speed of light limit. He felt that this was a \"spooky\" phenomenon because it challenged our classical understanding of space and time, and it seemed to defy the fundamental principles of causality. In essence, Einstein was saying that if entanglement is real, then it's not just a matter of particles being linked, but rather it's a fundamental aspect of the fabric of reality itself, which is unsettling to our intuitive understanding of the world.",
      "source": "target",
